Julius Caesar collapsed at the battle of Thapsus in 46BC . 
  Historians have long believed this was result of an epileptic attack . 
  But new research suggests he may have been suffering from a series of mini-strokes that affected his mental and physical state . 
  Doctors at Imperial College London took a new look at his symptoms in Greek and Roman documents . 
  They found he suffered from vertigo, dizziness and weakness in his limbs . 
 